Node.Notes: Uncertain. Roads/paths, which in context likely the pilgrimage roads of ascent to the temple (pilgrimage also supported by LXX).

Some derive the name Baca from balsam tree and assumes the valley known for these trees, which grow in arid places. Some see a play on the sound, which is like the verb "to weep" (so the Valley of Baca [Dry Place] is also the Valley of Baca [Weeping]).

Uncertain. Some see "our shield" as a parallel vocative reference to God (supported by LXX). Tree assumes "our shield" is reference to the king (your anointed one in second half): "Look on our shield [in favor], O God ..."
Text reads "a day in your courts is [better] than a thousand,” without indicating where those thousand days would be spent. Most assume anywhere else/elsewhere implied.
Uncertain what figure of sun stands for. May be similar to "my light and my salvation" in ps27:1. Perhaps passages like is60:19, 20; ma3:20; rev21:23 related.
